<p>Hold onto your rapidly accelerating, non-locomoting feet — Segway is back with a new product: Segway skates.</p>
<p>Yes, seriously.</p>
<p>As <em><a href="https://www.fastcompany.com/90242145/segway-is-back-and-its-coming-for-your-last-shred-of-dignity?partner=rss&amp;utm_source=twitter.com&amp;utm_medium=social&amp;utm_campaign=rss+fastcompany&amp;utm_content=rss">Fast Company reported</a></em>, the company best known for making tourists stand out even more hilariously has met its crowdfunding goal for The Drift W1, a pair of self-balancing e-skates. In fact, the <a href="https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/the-drift-w1-experience-segway-s-new-age-e-skates#/">Indiegogo campaign</a> raised almost <em>30 times</em> its funding goal, with two weeks to spare.</p>
<h2><strong>OKAY BUT WHAT?</strong></h2>
<p>Wondering where Segway has been over the past few years? Well, the company&#8217;s actually been around, making a decent bit of money after <a href="https://futurism.com/ninebot-segway-adorable-helper-robot-segway-can-ride/">being purchased by Ninebot</a>, a Beijing robotics company that makes little self-balancing helper bots.</p>
<h2><strong>SERIOUSLY: WHAT.</strong></h2>
<p>Let’s not ignore the extremely dumb-looking elephant in the room. If you thought scooters were annoying, just wait until the sidewalks are flooded by bros zipping around on their high-tech Heelys. Segway plans on shipping The Drift W1 to Indiegogo backers in October. The company is hoping to capitalize on the <a href="https://futurism.com/hoverboard-injuries/">hoverboard craze</a>, though at a retail price of $499 (a hoverboard typically runs <a href="https://www.amazon.com/slp/best-hoverboards/2mfj29cvetjp6kk">about $200</a>) it’s unclear if these skates can ever become as popular.</p>
